import DocsLayout from '../../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import CodeBlock from '../../../../../components/CodeBlock.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../../components/Callout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Architecture" description="Plan the technical architecture for Vinyl Vault, with critical attention to API integration and hallucination prevention.">
  <h1 class="mb-6">Architecture</h1>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Same process as P3 — prompt with PRD + design spec + architecture template. The critical new content is how the architecture handles third-party API integration.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">The prompt</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Paste this into Claude along with the architecture template, your PRD, and your design spec:</p>

  <CodeBlock copy>{`Here is the PRD and design spec for an online record store:

[Paste your PRD]
[Paste your design spec]

Tech stack: React frontend, FastAPI backend, PostgreSQL, Stripe for payments, Google Maps for store location, Docker, GitHub Actions CI, Gemini reviewer.

Using the following architecture template, generate a complete architecture document. For each third-party integration, specify:
1. Which specific API/product you're using and why
2. The data flow between your app and the external service
3. How API keys are managed
4. How webhooks are handled (for Stripe)

The architecture must include a CLAUDE.md file with this explicit instruction: "Do not use any Stripe API method without citing the documentation URL. Do not use any Google Maps API method without citing the documentation URL."

[Paste architecture template from /templates]`}</CodeBlock>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Key decisions</h2>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Stripe: which product?</h3>
  <div class="overflow-x-auto mb-6">
    <table class="w-full text-sm border-collapse">
      <thead>
        <tr class="bg-bg-muted">
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Product</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">What it is</th>
          <th class="text-left px-4 py-3 font-semibold border-b border-border">Recommendation</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Stripe Checkout</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Hosted payment page — Stripe handles the entire UI</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Simplest. Recommended for this project.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border bg-bg-subtle">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Stripe Elements</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Embeddable payment form components</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">More control, more work. Valid choice.</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="border-b border-border">
          <td class="px-4 py-3 font-medium">Custom (PaymentIntents)</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Low-level API for custom payment flows</td>
          <td class="px-4 py-3 text-text-secondary">Overkill for a small record store.</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Google Maps: embed vs API?</h3>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">Embed (iframe):</strong> Simple, no JavaScript needed. Good enough for a single location. Recommended.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">JavaScript API:</strong> Full control — custom markers, styling. More complex, requires an API key with billing enabled.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">For showing a single store pin, the embed is sufficient.</p>

  <h3 class="mb-3 mt-6">Database schema</h3>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">Simpler than it sounds. No user accounts means no users table. The core tables: <strong class="text-text">products</strong> (records in the catalog), <strong class="text-text">orders</strong> (completed purchases), and <strong class="text-text">order_items</strong> (which records were in each order). Check that the architecture includes these and that the relationships make sense.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Create an OpenAPI spec</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Before Claude Code writes any backend code, generate an API contract. This is a YAML file that defines every endpoint, its parameters, and its response format — before any implementation exists.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Add this to your Claude prompt:</p>

  <CodeBlock copy>{`Generate an OpenAPI 3.0 spec for this architecture. Define every endpoint, request body, response schema, and error format. Output as a YAML file called openapi.yaml.`}</CodeBlock>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Save the generated <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">openapi.yaml</code> in your project root. This becomes the API contract — implementation must match it.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this matters:</strong> FastAPI auto-generates OpenAPI documentation at <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">/docs</code>. Once Claude Code builds the API, visit <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">localhost:8000/docs</code> and compare the auto-generated spec against your original <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">openapi.yaml</code>. If they diverge, the implementation drifted from the contract. Fix it before moving on.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Create an architecture diagram</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Open <a href="https://excalidraw.com">Excalidraw</a> (excalidraw.com, free) or <a href="https://app.diagrams.net">Draw.io</a> (app.diagrams.net, free). Create a diagram showing the system architecture:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-4">
    <li>Browser → Frontend (React)</li>
    <li>Frontend → API (FastAPI)</li>
    <li>API → Database (PostgreSQL)</li>
    <li>API → Stripe (external service)</li>
    <li>Frontend → Google Maps (external service)</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">This diagram is a deliverable — save it in the repo as <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">architecture-diagram.png</code>. It helps anyone (including future you) understand the system at a glance.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">API documentation verification</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This is the core P4 skill, and it starts in the architecture.</p>

  <Callout variant="warning">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>When Claude generates Stripe integration code, it will hallucinate.</strong> Real-looking but wrong — deprecated endpoints, invented parameters, incorrect response formats. The architecture must build verification into the process, not treat it as an afterthought.</p>
  </Callout>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">The architecture should specify:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-text">All Stripe API calls must be verified against <a href="https://stripe.com/docs">stripe.com/docs</a> before implementation</strong></li>
    <li><strong class="text-text">All Google Maps integration must be verified against <a href="https://developers.google.com/maps">Google's documentation</a></strong></li>
    <li>The CLAUDE.md must include: <em>"Do not use any Stripe API method without citing the documentation URL"</em></li>
  </ul>

  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">This CLAUDE.md instruction forces Claude Code to reference the docs when writing integration code. It won't eliminate hallucinations — but it gives you a clear signal when verification is needed and makes it easier to check.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Review guidance</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">When reviewing the architecture, check everything from P3 (over-engineering, schema, endpoints, CLAUDE.md consistency) plus:</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-6">
    <li>Does the Stripe integration section reference a specific Stripe product (Checkout, Elements)?</li>
    <li>Is webhook handling defined — which events, how signatures are verified, what happens when a webhook arrives?</li>
    <li>Are API keys managed via environment variables with <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">.env</code> in <code class="bg-bg-muted px-1.5 py-0.5 rounded text-xs font-mono">.gitignore</code>?</li>
    <li>Does the CLAUDE.md anti-scope match the PRD? Does it include the doc-citation instruction?</li>
  </ul>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Save the architecture and CLAUDE.md as separate files.</strong> The CLAUDE.md goes into the project root. The doc-citation instruction is the most important line in it.</p>
  </Callout>

  <details class="my-8 border border-border rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
    <summary class="px-6 py-4 bg-bg-muted cursor-pointer font-semibold text-sm">The landscape: API specification</summary>
    <div class="px-6 py-4">
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mb-4">You're using OpenAPI/Swagger to define your REST API contract. This is the most common approach, but not the only one.</p>
      <div class="space-y-3">
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">OpenAPI/Swagger</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">The standard for REST APIs. YAML or JSON format. Widely supported by tools, code generators, and documentation platforms. What you're using in this project.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">GraphQL Schema</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">A query language where the client specifies exactly which fields it wants. One endpoint instead of many. Used by GitHub, Shopify, and Facebook.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">gRPC Proto Files</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">Binary protocol using Protocol Buffers. Fast and type-safe. Common in microservices and internal APIs where performance matters.</span></p></div>
        <div><p class="text-sm"><strong class="text-text">tRPC</strong> — <span class="text-text-secondary">End-to-end type safety between TypeScript frontend and backend. No separate API definition — the types are the contract. Popular in the Next.js ecosystem.</span></p></div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary mt-4">OpenAPI is the right starting point. When you encounter GraphQL or gRPC in the wild, you'll recognise they solve the same problem — defining a contract between client and server — with different trade-offs.</p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <div class="mt-8 p-6 bg-primary-bg rounded-lg border border-primary/20 text-center">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-2">Next: implementation</h2>
    <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Architecture is done. Time to build it.</p>
    <a
      href="/web-dev/projects/4/implementation"
      class="inline-block bg-primary hover:bg-primary-dark text-white font-semibold py-3 px-6 rounded-md transition-colors min-h-[44px]"
    >
      Implementation →
    </a>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
